a note to Dr. Swan.

589
00:33:30,509 --> 00:33:32,211
Look at me.

590
00:33:33,079 --> 00:33:34,580
He's right here.

591
00:33:34,613 --> 00:33:37,216
Yes, yes, I know. I know.
But, uh, this is faster.

592
00:33:48,427 --> 00:33:51,297
You talk to machines
more than you talk to people.

593
00:34:01,807 --> 00:34:03,475
Okay.

594
00:34:03,509 --> 00:34:05,211
Open the book.

595
00:34:13,152 --> 00:34:16,788
MITCH: Books by great authors 
 are the best teachers 
 in the world.

596
00:34:16,822 --> 00:34:20,192
They can instruct you 
 on anything you need to know 
 in life.

597
00:34:20,226 --> 00:34:22,094
The way to make reading 
 meaningful

598
00:34:22,128 --> 00:34:25,431
is to find stories and books 
 that interest you

599
00:34:25,464 --> 00:34:27,599
and reflect the way you're
thinking and feeling.

600
00:34:27,633 --> 00:34:31,503
That way, they come alive
and it sticks in your mind.

601
00:34:31,537 --> 00:34:35,341
They create mental pictures
that you can hold on to.

602
00:34:35,374 --> 00:34:39,345
Books about history can
make you a part
of what's gone on before

603
00:34:39,378 --> 00:34:41,713
and, oh... Poetry.

604
00:34:42,781 --> 00:34:45,184
Poetry speaks to your soul.

605
00:34:47,286 --> 00:34:49,087
Connects you to another being.

606
00:34:55,161 --> 00:34:56,762
At the checkout counter,
the clerk says,

607
00:34:56,795 --> 00:34:59,365
"That'll be $17,
33 cents, please."

